  I have thought about the same thing Hoppkins.  I personally think that, religion is an excercise for a balanced mental state.  Religion IMO being different from spirituality.  Now there are a few different ways I look at this:  one, there are elements in hinduism, buddhism, taoism, shintoism etc...(most every religion I know of) that are good.  Good meaning, the search for truth and love.  Two:  Christianity is a 'word'.  Its also known as an idea to the people who have been educated in its meaning.  BUT that does not mean hinduism, buddhism, taoism, shintoism etc... are not christian ideals.  They have the same desire for truth and love that God and Jesus represnt in Christianity.  So in a literary sense there is very little difference between all 'good' religions.  <br>
  I believe what you are ultimately refering to is the attitude some, so-called 'Christians' have when they exclaim, &quot;YOUR GOING TO HELL if you dont believe in Jesus&quot;.  Not sure about you but i want to rip their nuts off and nail them to a cross.  They make me sick to my stomach.  ULTIMATELY, everyone will know truth and love(IMO) through God and Jesus.I try my best 99% of the time to understand.  SO, it really doen't matter if you take the christian highway, the hindu express, the buddhist boat or the shinto chevrolet.  The path of love and truth eventually leads to the same destination.  I personally love the story of Jesus and want my life to reflect his and my death to reflect his.  The craziest thing about the world is how much love you have(or will have) for your children.  I would gladly die for my kids any day of the week.  But heres the crazy part of it.  EVERYONE is a child of someone.  We should all understand that every person on this board, every person at your workplace, every person in your neighborhood, every person in the world is a loved child of someone. You can't touch that kind of love with all the money/material in the world.  Nothing is more powerful.  And nothing can stop seekers of love and truth from getting to their destination.  No matter what 'word' they use to describe their beliefs.  The only thing that can be changed about the journey for love and truth is the path that is taken.  Take the short road for obvious reasons, take the long road if you insist on asserting your freewill.  Neither matter really.  Both are interesting/exciting and are full of all types of emotions.  At this point in my life, I am outside the castle of love and truth playing golf; ocassionaly 'slicing'(term used in golf indicating a 'foul ball', if you will) and breaking a window in God's castle.  Yea, I get the feeling he is bitching me out but I tend to laugh at him (similar to how I acted towards my parents when I was a teenager).  After a while, God redirects my golfball using the winds-of-truth and proceeds to pelt me in the ass with the past 50 balls I have sliced(most of the balls, mind you, were 'sliced' on purpose in order to test the boundaries of love and truth).  &quot;Damn that shit hurts&quot;  Then I ask for the band-aid of love and I get it.  Then immediately slice another ball on purpose and laugh my ass off.  <br>
  Anyway I'm sure you understand the analogy and can make your own story using many creative comparisons to describe your relationship.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uhoppkins.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hoppkins</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 207<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/21/01 1:59:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=373>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://freespace.virgin.net/lol.marcus/garnett3.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Do you believe in god?</span><hr size=1> o.k intresting post...objective<br>
